blocks.text:
Launching any mail service is not just about "making an interface." This is working with deeply ingrained habits of people, with privacy, trust, and a huge number of edge cases.

We faced several challenges:
- the market is overflowing with giants — how do we stand out?
- email clients are often confusing, heavy, and overloaded with features;
- users don't trust the new services in terms of security;
- UX solutions must be perfect, because mail is a tool for every day;
- the end-to-end encryption format adds complexity: errors are unacceptable, and there are a lot of scenarios "behind the scenes".

We realized that if we want to make a difference, the product must be simple, powerful, and honest at the same time.
So it all started with research.

I did a lot of UX research:
- interviews with users from different countries;
- competitor analysis — from Gmail to Proton and Superhuman;
- research scenarios in which people most often make mistakes;
- barriers to security and trust;
- usage patterns in different age groups.
The main conclusion is that people want an email that "just works", does not load their heads and does not hide important things behind unnecessary noise. They are also very afraid of losing their data or being hacked.

This has become the foundation of the UX architecture.
